<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,763,1111]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Comments: This is the only species included in the genus so far, and was described based on material from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,260,871,895]" name="Honduras" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Honduras</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hussey" box="[275,427,871,895]" firstAuthor="Hussey" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="115 - 119" refId="ref38433" refString="Hussey, R. F. (1925) A new Hydrometridae genus from Honduras (Hemiptera). Bulletin of the Brooklyn Entomological Society, 20, 115 - 119." type="journal article" year="1925">Hussey 1925</bibRefCitation>
). Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[520,709,871,895]" firstAuthor="Andersen" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="301 - 316" refId="ref33829" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1977) A new primitive genus and species of Hydrometridae (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha) with cladistic analysis of relationships within the family. Entomologica Scandinavica, 8, 301 - 316." type="journal article" year="1977">Andersen (1977)</bibRefCitation>
included 
<collectingCountry box="[821,889,871,895]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[946,997,872,895]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Peru</collectingCountry>
in the distributional list of the species, but mistakenly reported 
<collectingCountry box="[423,615,908,932]" name="Belize" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">British Honduras</collectingCountry>
instead of 
<collectingCountry box="[737,850,908,932]" name="Honduras" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Honduras</collectingCountry>
. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus and Polhemus" box="[890,1248,908,932]" firstAuthor="Polhemus" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref42277" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. (1995) A primitive new species of Hydrometra from Tahiti (Heteroptera: Hydrometridae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers, 43, 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1995">Polhemus and Polhemus (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, another country is added to the species geographical distribution: 
<collectingCountry box="[707,877,943,967]" name="French Guiana" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
. The mistaken record from 
<collectingCountry box="[1189,1382,943,967]" name="Belize" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">British Honduras</collectingCountry>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[255,444,980,1004]" firstAuthor="Andersen" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="301 - 316" refId="ref33829" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1977) A new primitive genus and species of Hydrometridae (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha) with cladistic analysis of relationships within the family. Entomologica Scandinavica, 8, 301 - 316." type="journal article" year="1977">Andersen (1977)</bibRefCitation>
was repeated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh and Slater" box="[638,911,980,1004]" firstAuthor="Schuh" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref43078" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Slater, J. A. (1995) True Bugs of the World (Hemiptera: Heteroptera) Classification and Natural History. Cornell University Press, New York, 336 pp." type="book" year="1995">Schuh and Slater (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, and no details are given in any of these works about the distribution of the species or the origin of the material from 
<collectingCountry box="[927,1095,1015,1039]" name="French Guiana" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1105,1176,1015,1039]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1235,1290,1016,1039]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Peru</collectingCountry>
. Considering the general distribution of the species, it is possible that the records from 
<collectingCountry box="[969,1037,1052,1076]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
are derived from material collected on the North Region, probably on PA or AM.
</paragraph>
